# üé¨ IMDB Movie Data Analysis

This project performs **Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)** on the IMDB Movie Dataset using Python. The goal is to uncover meaningful insights into **movie trends, audience ratings, box office revenues, and genre performance** through statistical and visual exploration.

---

## üìä Objectives

- Gain a comprehensive understanding of the IMDB dataset structure  
- Explore distributions of key metrics: ratings, revenues, and metascores  
- Analyze **genre-based trends** and their correlations  
- Visualize insights using `matplotlib` and `seaborn`

---

## üìÅ Dataset Overview

- **Filename:** `IMDB-Movie-Data.csv`  
- **Source:** [Kaggle IMDB Dataset](https://www.kaggle.com/datasets)  
- **Description:** Metadata for 1,000 popular IMDB movies, including:

  | Column             | Description                  |
  |--------------------|------------------------------|
  | Title              | Name of the movie            |
  | Genre              | Genre(s) of the movie        |
  | Director           | Movie director               |
  | Actors             | Leading actors               |
  | IMDB Rating        | Audience rating              |
  | Metascore          | Critic rating                |
  | Revenue (Millions) | Box office revenue           |
  | Year               | Year of release              |

---

## üõ†Ô∏è Tools & Libraries

- Python 3.x  
- NumPy  
- Pandas  
- Matplotlib  
- Seaborn  
- Jupyter Notebook

---

## üìà Exploratory Highlights

- Dataset overview: `shape`, `info()`, `describe()`, `head()`  
- Handling and visualizing **missing data**  
- **Revenue trends** across release years  
- Distribution analysis of **IMDB ratings** and **metascores**  
- **Genre-wise performance** breakdown  
- **Correlation heatmaps** for numerical features

---

## üöÄ Getting Started

To run the analysis locally:

```bash
git clone https://github.com/Manavdarji2/imdb-movie-eda.git
```

Then open the notebook in Jupyter and follow along with the cells to explore the data.

